The neighborhoods hadn’t exactly prepared for a pandemic, but over the past few years, nine of them formed city-sanctioned cultural districts.
E accounted for crisis, according to Julia Sabory, cultural districts manager with the Mayor’s Office of Housing and Community Development.
Even if only a handful of tourists visited San Francisco during the next two years, that would still mean $2.43 million in 2022.
In the Tenderloin, for instance, the work of the Compton’s Transgender Cultural District has essentially gone online — a sensible move but perhaps a vexing one.
Peter Lawrence Kane is the communications manager of San Francisco Pride and a former editor of SF Weekly.